A field experiment conducted by Harvard Business School researchers titled "Is Hybrid Work the Best of Both Worlds?" provides causal evidence on work arrangements. The researchers found that workers who spent around two days in the office each week self-reported greater work-life balance, more job satisfaction, and lower isolation from colleagues compared to workers who spent more or fewer days in the office. Furthermore, an intermediate number of days in the office resulted in more emails sent and increased novelty of work products. The study concludes that intermediate hybrid work is the sweet spot, allowing workers to capture the benefits of a productive workplace while maintaining flexibility.
